#Text=Fundy National Park
#Text=Fundy National
#Text=Park
#Text=is a national park near Alma in New Brunswick , Canada .
#Text=Understand
#Text=The park has a rugged coastline which rises up to the Canadian Highlands , the highest tides in the world and more than 25 waterfalls .
#Text=The park covers an area of 207 km ² ( 80 sq mi ) along Goose Bay , the northwestern branch of the Bay of Fundy .
#Text=When you looks across the Bay , you can see the northern Nova Scotia coast .
#Text=A variety of scientific projects are ongoing in the park , with the primary focus on monitoring the park 's ecology .
#Text=Projects have focused on re-establishing aquatic connectivity in the park ( Bennett Lake Dam , new Culverts , Dickson Brook restoration .
#Text=Species such as the endangered Inner Bay of Fundy Salmon , Martens and Fishers ( members of the weasel family ) , brook trout , eel , and moose are monitored regularly .
#Text=Park office , ☏ +1 506-887-6000 , ✉ fundy.info@pc.gc.ca .
#Text=Landscape
#Text=The park is located in the Level III- Eastern Temperate Forests ( Maine-New Brunswick Plains and Hills ) ecoregion .
#Text=The park is situated in two distinct ecoregions .
#Text=The southern section of the park falls in the Fundy Coast ecoregion .
#Text=This region experiences cool , wet summers and mild , rainy winters .
#Text=Its coniferous forest consists of red spruce , balsam fir , and red maple with some white spruce , and white and yellow birch .
#Text=Some sugar maple and beech trees are also found here at higher elevations .
#Text=The northern section of the park falls in the Southern New Brunswick Uplands ecoregion .
#Text=This ecoregion experiences summers that are warm and rainy , and winters that are mild and snowy .
#Text=Its mixed-wood forest contains mainly sugar and red maple , white and red spruce and balsam fir trees .
#Text=The park is in the New England-Acadian forest ecoregion .
#Text=Flora
#Text=The park is home to 658 species of vascular plants , 276 species of bryophytes , and more than 400 species of lichens .

#Text=The Fundy forest is generally a mixed-wood forest composed of red spruce ( Picea rubens ) , balsam fir ( Abies balsamea ) , yellow birch ( Betula alleghaniensis ) , white birch ( Betulla papyrifera ) , sugar maple ( Acer saccharum ) , and red maple ( Acer rubrum ) .
#Text=The mixed-wood forest floor is blanketed with moss , wood fern ( Dryopteris ) , and bunchberry ( Cornus canadensis ) .
#Text=Pure hardwood stands ( distinguishable communities of tree species within a forest ) account for 5.4 % of the Fundy forest cover .
#Text=The most abundant pure hardwood stands are yellow birch ( Betula alleghaniensis ) and white birch ( Betulla papyrifera ) .
#Text=There are also some sugar maple ( Acer saccharum ) , red maple ( Acer rubrum ) , and beech ( Fagus ) stands .
#Text=Carolina springbeauty ( Claytonia caroliniana ) and trout-lily ( Erythronium americanum ) bloom in the hardwood forest every year .
#Text=The coniferous forest in the park represents the boreal element of Fundy ’s forest cover .
#Text=Although pure stands of conifer are rare in the park , the Fundy forest has some of the last pure stands of red spruce ( Picea rubens ) found in eastern North America .
#Text=The bogs of the park are blanketed with sphagnum moss ( Sphagnum ) from which grow black spruce ( Picea mariana ) and Eastern larch ( Larix laricina ) .
#Text=Within the park ’s Caribou Plain bog , three carnivorous plant species are found : pitcher plant ( Sarracenia purpurea ) , sundew ( Drosera anglica ) , and bladderwort ( Utricularia ) .
#Text=Some rare plant species are also found in the park .

#Text=Bird’s-eye primrose ( Primula farinosa ) is found along the Point Wolfe and Goose River coastal cliffs , and several other rare flora species , namely slender spikemoss ( Selaginella viridissima ) , squashberry ( Viburnum edule ) , green spleenwort ( Asplenium viride ) , rare sedges , and fir clubmoss ( Huperzia selago ) , are found along the eastern branch of the Point Wolfe River and the lower part of Bennett Brook .
#Text=Fauna

#Text=Animals that inhabit this national park are moose , snowshoe hares , chipmunks , cormorants , red squirrels , pileated woodpeckers , little brown bats , peregrine falcons , black bears , coyotes , beavers , white-tailed deer , white-winged crossbills , various mice and shrews , juncos , sandpipers , raccoons , warblers , plovers , great blue herons , and northern flying squirrels .
#Text=Fees and permits
#Text=Daily/seasonal ( 2018 ) :
#Text=Senior $6.80/$ 34.30
#Text=Youth and children free
#Text=Family/group $15.70/$ 78.50
#Text=Parks Canada Passes
#Text=The Discovery Pass provides unlimited admission for a full year at over 80 Parks Canada places that typically charge a daily entrance fee
#Text=It provides faster entry and is valid for 12 months from date of purchase .
#Text=Prices for 2018 ( taxes included ) :
#Text=Family/group ( up to 7 people in a vehicle ) : $ 136.40
#Text=Children and youth ( 0-17 ) : free
#Text=Senior ( 65+ ) : $ 57.90
#Text=The Cultural Access Pass : people who have received their Canadian citizenship in the past year can qualify for free entry to some sites .
#Text=Fishing ( 2018 ) : Daily $ 9.80 , annual $ 34.30
#Text=Golf ( 2018 summer/shoulder season ) :
#Text=Seasonal : junior $ 142.25 , adult $ 456.30 , couple $ 686.90 , family $ 809.50
#Text=Do
#Text=At low tide , park visitors can explore the ocean floor where a variety of sea creatures ( e. g. , dog whelk , periwinkles , various seaweeds ) cling to life .
#Text=At high tide , the ocean floor disappears under 15 m ( 50 ft ) of salt water .
#Text=Paddle in a kayak as the waters rise up to 12 metres or more .
#Text=Walk the otherworldly sea floor at low tide .
#Text=There are 25 hiking trails throughout the park .
#Text=The Caribou Plains trail and boardwalk provides access to upland forest and bog habitats .
#Text=Dickson Falls is the most popular trail in the park .
#Text=The Dobson Trail and Fundy Footpath extend out of the park to Riverview and to St. Martins respectively .
#Text=A unique red-painted covered bridge is located at Point Wolfe .
#Text=Park amenities include a golf course , a heated saltwater swimming pool , three campgrounds , and a network of over 100 km of hiking and biking trails .
#Text=During the winter , Fundy National Park is available for day use , at one 's own risk for skiing , snowshoeing , tobagganing , and winter walking .
